Formal Verification and Zero-Trust Enforcement for the CXL Fabric Manager Control Plane

M.N. Srivatsa Bharadwaj
Samsung Semiconductor Research India (SSIR), Bengaluru, India

---

ABSTRACT

Compute Express Link (CXL) 3.x introduces the Fabric Manager (FM) as the central control plane for memory disaggregation in multi-tenant datacenters. While prior work focuses on device-level security (SPDM, TSP) [1][2], the FM control plane lacks authentication and authorization—a gap we identify as architectural. This paper presents the first formal security analysis of the FMAPI control plane, modeling it as a state machine with three security properties: confinement, non-bypassability, and availability. Using TLA+ bounded model checking with Tenants={A,B}, Devices={D1-D4}, Ports={P1-P4}, and Extents={E1-E4}, we demonstrate that the baseline CXL FM specification permits three architectural attack classes (cross-tenant device hijack, fabric denial-of-service, DCD memory theft) and one implementation-level stress attack (control-plane exhaustion). We propose ZTFM (Zero-Trust Fabric Manager) , a reference monitor enforcing SPDM-bound authentication, ownership graphs, and capability-based authorization. For the modeled state space (2.3×10⁶ states), TLA+ model checking found no reachable state violating security properties under ZTFM. Leveraging the pairwise, tenant-symmetric structure of the confinement invariant, we further argue via a small-model/symmetry-reduction theorem [11] that Theorem 1 generalizes to arbitrary tenant counts, not merely the bounded instance checked. Implemented in a QEMU-based CXL fabric emulator, ZTFM blocks all attacks with <5μs overhead and scales to 64 tenants with 6.12 μs FM latency. We release the first reproducible artifact for CXL FM security, demonstrating that the vulnerability may be inherited by FM implementations that do not add authentication and authorization beyond the baseline model.

Keywords—CXL, Fabric Manager, Formal Verification, Zero-Trust, TLA+, Memory Disaggregation

