2.2 Threat Model

Attacker Capabilities:

· Network or PCIe access to the FM (same fabric)
· Ability to send arbitrary FMAPI commands
· May be a legitimate tenant in the multi-tenant fabric
· Cannot: Compromise device firmware, break cryptographic keys, or physically tamper with hardware

Attacker Goal: Manipulate fabric resources to violate confidentiality, integrity, or availability.

Assumptions:

· FM is reachable (no network segmentation)
· SPDM protects device identity but not FMAPI commands
· Standard CXL 3.1 compliant implementation

2.3 Related Work and Novelty

CXL Security. The CXL specification [1] defines SPDM [2] for device authentication and IDE (Integrity and Data Encryption) for transport security. However, as the specification's threat table shows [1, Table 11-4], these mechanisms protect against threats like packet interception and device impersonation—not unauthorized control-plane commands. Stark et al. [4] provide a comprehensive analysis of CXL's protection mechanisms, noting that CXL relies on "coarse-grained protection" with "few ranges" that "will necessarily be large." They identify that the Fabric Manager has "no defined interface" for changing memory mappings and transferring access rights. This confirms the architectural gap our work addresses. Our work is the first to formalize and verify a complete FM security architecture.

PCIe and Memory Security. Prior PCIe security work focuses on ACS (Access Control Services) and AER for device isolation. These mechanisms operate below the FM and cannot enforce tenant-level ownership policies. ZTFM fills this gap at the control plane level.

Control Plane Security. SDN controllers face similar challenges [5]; NVMe-oF introduced authentication but lacks capability-based delegation [6]. ZTFM adapts these lessons to CXL with formal verification.

Formal Methods. Lamport's TLA+ [7] has been applied to distributed systems; prior work on AXI protocol security verification [8] demonstrates the value of formal methods for interconnects. We extend this to CXL fabric management.

Generalization Techniques. Bounded model checking inherently verifies only a finite instance of a parameterized system. Grundmann and Hartenstein [12] address this exact limitation for the Lightning Network by combining TLC-checked small instances with a refinement chain to justify correctness for arbitrary participant counts. We adopt an analogous strategy: rather than re-running TLC at increasing scale, we invoke classical symmetry-reduction theory [11] to argue that our pairwise-quantified invariants admit a small-model property, allowing the |T|=2 result to extend formally to arbitrary |T|.

