4. FMATTACK: ARCHITECTURAL ATTACKS

4.1 Attack Classification

Class Attack Property Violated
Architectural ATK-1: Cross-tenant device hijack Confinement
Architectural ATK-2: Fabric denial-of-service Availability
Architectural ATK-3: DCD memory theft Confinement
Implementation ATK-5: Control-plane exhaustion Availability

4.2 Architectural Attack Descriptions

ATK-1: Cross-Tenant Device Hijack

```
Victim tenant allocates Device A
Attacker sends UNBIND_VPPB(Device A)
Attacker sends BIND_VPPB(Device A, Attacker)
Attacker now has CXL.mem access to victim's device
```

ATK-2: Fabric Denial-of-Service

```
Attacker identifies victim's upstream port
Attacker sends SET_PHY_PORT_STATE(port, DOWN)
All victim devices disconnected
```

ATK-3: DCD Memory Theft

```
Victim has DCD extent E
Attacker sends DCD_RELEASE(E)
Attacker sends DCD_ADD(E, Attacker)
Attacker reads residual memory
```

Key insight: The CXL specification does not explicitly require DCD zeroing-on-release. As noted in the CXL 2.0 FAQ, "Prior to UNBIND the host can clear the memory contents and after the UNBIND the Fabric Manager can clear the memory contents. Good system practice would be to use both methods prior to BINDing to a new host." [3] This is a recommendation, not a requirement—our model treats zeroing as vendor-defined.

4.3 Implementation Stress Attack

ATK-5: Control-Plane Exhaustion

Mechanism: Attacker sends repeated BIND_VPPB/UNBIND_VPPB on a single vPPB.

Complexity Derivation: Each operation triggers topology rediscovery: O(N² + M²).

Measured Profiling (from emulator):

Operations/sec CPU Utilization
0 (idle) 2%
10 9%
50 47%
100 94%
200 100%

