Theorem 1 (Confinement Preservation): For the modeled state space with Tenants={A,B}, Devices={D1-D4}, Ports={P1-P4}, and Extents={E1-E4}, TLA+ model checking found no reachable state violating confinement under ZTFM.

5.4 Generalization Beyond the Bounded Instance

Bounded model checking over Tenants={A,B} establishes Theorem 1 only for |T|=2. We argue the result generalizes to arbitrary |T|=n as follows.

Each ZTFM invariant is a universally quantified, pairwise condition over T. Confinement (I1) is ∀ t1,t2 ∈ T: (O(d)=t1 ∧ Access(t2,d)) ⇒ t1=t2; DCD isolation (I2), port ownership (I3), and rate limiting (I4) are likewise defined per-resource or per-tenant, never jointly over three or more tenants simultaneously. Furthermore, ZTFM's enforcement logic—HMAC token validation, ownership-register lookup, and rate-counter increment—evaluates each request against exactly one caller identity and one resource owner, with no transition rule that special-cases a particular tenant's identity. The transition relation is therefore symmetric under any permutation of T.

Under these conditions, classical symmetry-reduction results [11] establish a small-model property for safety invariants of this form: if a counterexample to a pairwise-quantified safety invariant exists for some |T|=n, a counterexample of the same structure exists for |T|=2, since any violating transition involves at most two tenant identities (the resource's owner and the unauthorized accessor). Equivalently, checking |T|=2 is necessary and sufficient to detect all violations of I1–I4 for any |T|≥2 under a tenant-symmetric transition relation.

We therefore claim Theorem 1 extends to arbitrary tenant counts. This claim is consistent with, though not separately re-verified against, our empirical scalability measurements in Section 8.4, which confirm bounded authorization-lookup latency growth up to 256 tenants without observing any ZTFM invariant violation in the emulator.

We note one caveat: this argument assumes the bounded device, port, and extent parameters (D, P, E) do not interact with tenant count in a way that breaks symmetry—e.g., that no fixed-size resource pool creates tenant-count-dependent contention that the model omits. We leave full mechanized verification of this generalization (e.g., via TLAPS or a parameterized model checker) to future work, and flag it explicitly as a soundness assumption rather than a machine-checked fact.

