7. SECURITY ARCHITECTURE DISCUSSION

7.1 Why SPDM Alone Fails

SPDM [2] protects device-to-requester authentication but does not extend to the FM control plane. An attacker can issue FMAPI commands without ever interacting with SPDM-protected devices. The attack surface is the FM API, not the device interface.

7.2 Why TLS Alone Fails

TLS provides transport-layer encryption and server authentication, but in multi-tenant environments, any tenant with valid credentials can authenticate. The problem is authorization, not authentication. TLS does not enforce ownership or delegation policies.

7.3 Why Capability Systems Are Necessary

ZTFM's capability-based approach resembles prior work in OS security [9][10] and SDN control planes [5]. As Stark et al. [4] observe, CXL's current protection model is "coarse-grained" and "inflexible," with few memory ranges per endpoint. Capability-based protection offers an alternative: architectural capabilities can provide "flexible, fine-grained memory protection" [4]. The key insight is that FMAPI commands require fine-grained authorization—not just a binary "authenticated vs. unauthenticated" check.

7.4 Why Ownership Graphs Are Necessary

Simple access control lists (ACLs) fail for CXL fabrics because resources have complex dependencies:

· DCD extents depend on parent devices
· Virtual ports depend on physical ports
· Tenants may have hierarchical relationships

Ownership graphs capture these dependencies and enable cascade revocation.

