11. CONCLUSION

This paper presented the first formal security analysis of the CXL Fabric Manager control plane. We modeled FMAPI as a TLA+ state machine with three security properties: confinement, non-bypassability, and availability. Through bounded model checking over 2.3×10⁶ states, we demonstrated that the baseline CXL specification permits three architectural attack classes and one implementation stress attack.

We proposed ZTFM, a zero-trust reference monitor with SPDM-bound authentication, ownership graphs, and capability-based authorization. For the modeled state space, TLA+ model checking found no reachable state violating security properties under ZTFM. We further argue, via classical symmetry-reduction theory, that this result generalizes from the checked 2-tenant instance to arbitrary tenant counts, subject to the tenant-symmetry assumption stated in Section 5.4. Experimental evaluation in a QEMU-based emulator shows ZTFM blocks all attacks with <5μs overhead and scales to 64 tenants with 6.12 μs FM latency.

We release the first open-source artifact for CXL FM security, demonstrating that the vulnerability may be inherited by FM implementations that do not add authentication and authorization beyond the baseline model. The CXL ecosystem must extend SPDM-style security to the control plane, not just the data plane.

